e altered the game’s texture. His teams provided models of racial integration in the 1950s and 1960s, and, in 1966, he became the first black coach of any major professional team sport. Yet, like no athlete before him, Russell challenged the politics of sport. Instead of displaying appreciative deference, he decried racist institutions, embraced his African roots, and challenged the nonviolent tenets of the civil rights movement. This beautifully written book—sophisticated, nuanced, and insightful—reveals a singular individual who expressed the dreams of Martin Luther King Jr. while echoing the warnings of Malcolm X.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBasketball playerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aBasketballzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  a1950s.  a1960s.  a20th century.  aafrican american athletes.  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aathlete biographies.  aathletes.  aathletics.  abasketball fans.  abasketball.  abill russell.  abiographical.  abiography.  ablack athletes.  aboston celtics.  acivil rights movement.  afamous athletes.  anba history.  anba.  anonfiction.  aprofessional basketball.  aracial integration.  asocial history.  asport politics.  asports biographies.  asports historians.  asports history.  asports journalism.  asports.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026979840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094576040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945760/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY